comment.body:
Thanks for the careful read. You're right on bugs 2 and 3 — `this.doc` and `this.awareness` are per-instance and dropped together with the provider, so there is no cross-instance accumulation. My PoC kept the mock awareness alive across teardown which created an artifact that does not reflect the real lifecycle. Treat those two as PoC noise rather than findings.

The shared-socket bug is the one that matters. Concrete fix: capture the three handlers as named class properties so `destroy()` can pass the handler reference to each `off()` call, instead of removing every listener for the event:

```ts
private _onDocUpdate = (data: ArrayBuffer) => { /* ... */ };
private _onAwarenessUpdate = (data: ArrayBuffer) => { /* ... */ };
private _onPresence = (presence: any) => { /* ... */ };

// connect():
this.socket.on('ydoc:document:update', this._onDocUpdate);
this.socket.on('ydoc:document:awareness:update', this._onAwarenessUpdate);
this.socket.on('ydoc:presence', this._onPresence);

// destroy():
this.socket.off('ydoc:document:update', this._onDocUpdate);
this.socket.off('ydoc:document:awareness:update', this._onAwarenessUpdate);
this.socket.off('ydoc:presence', this._onPresence);
```

This preserves listeners that other Provider instances registered on the shared singleton while still cleaning up the destroyed provider's own registrations — closes the editor-switch overlap window without affecting any other mounted editor.

